recordings.loc: Green Township (near  Mount Orab), Brown County, Ohio
recordings.rmk: Small edits were made to the original recording including noise reduction, fade in/out, and amplification. No splitting or shortening of intervals. The owls were recorded for more than one hour but this segment was selected as it had the least background noise to contend with. Rural habitat; large open fields with rolling / varied topography; a creek is surrounded by large mature trees (pine, oak, birch, maple) and meanders through the countryside. The owls (two males and one female) were heard calling back and forth. One of the males flew in and perched 50 ft. above the recorder. These are resident Great Horned Owls and we have witnessed the pair using the dead trees on the opposite side of our street as a perch over the past several years. Hearing a second male encroaching, the male perched above the recorder took flight in the direction of the other male and disappeared into the night. Shortly after the male departed, the female flew in and landed in the same tree and began calling. This is the female segment of the recording.

An excerpt from a much longer soundscape recording. I was set up to record bugling Rocky Mountain Elk (Cervus canadensis nelsoni) on their daily migration between the mountains and lowlands. recordings.rmk:
"Wac wac" call in response to playing a northern saw-whet owl recording.  A short time after this recording ended, I started hearing female squawk and male territorial calls from the same direction.  I didn't play any great horned owl vocalizations.  This is an uncommon GHOW vocalization, and to identify it, I compared this recording with one on the "Voices of North American Owls" CD.  I also compared the recording with spotted owl, long-eared owl, and even mule deer (which I saw nearby) recordings and was able to exclude those species.  A faint western screech owl is audible in the background and earlier I had also heard some whines from a northern saw-whet owl.

Habitat: Edge of an open forest with Coulter pine, canyon live oak, bigcone Douglas Fir, incense cedar, and chaparral  species.

Equipment: Olympus LS-10 with a Telinga 22 inch dish and a Sennheiser ME62 microphone.

recordings.loc: Greater Vancouver A (near  Delta), Greater Vancouver, British Columbia
recordings.rmk:
Recording made with Samsung phone and amplified with Audacity. Track is 4 minutes though the calls went on for 10-15 minutes. Recorded in front of my house, lots of tall cedars and firs in the area. Background sound is a water bubbler fountain. Lots of ambient light from houses that made it hard to see anything against the night sky. Adult GHO has been seen previously in the backyard but no adults were heard at this time.

There were certainly 2, maybe 3, individuals moving between the trees, maybe 30-40 feet up. One bird did fly overhead, silently, at about 30-40 feet but all I could discern was the silhouette. It was large, but smaller than a Bald Eagle (which are very common around here). Twice I heard not just the call but also the clacking of the bird's bill, but that was before I got the phone out to make the recording.

Identification was based on a similar recording found on the Audubon site at <https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/great-horned-owl> under a call named "immature calls with bill snapping".

original description:

9 calls from the bird in this particular recording, and the calls are 15 to 20 seconds apart. These calls are the only sounds heard from this bird, and they have been occurring nearly every night for approximately 3 weeks, starting in early evening and sometimes going nearly until morning light. The bird never calls during daylight hours.

The bird perches high in trees when calling. It occasionally flies to different trees, and does not make sounds while flying, but will begin calling once perched. It seems to turn it's head (or possibly it's whole body) to call in different directions, an inference I make because of the difference in volume of the calls while I am standing in one position.

The environment is a large cemetery, bordered by a densely wooded park. The bird is making these calls while perched in trees in the cemetery, which has a lot of open spaces. The only bodies of water nearby are the Iowa river (about 1 mile away) and Lake McBride/Coralville Reservoir (about 5 miles away). 

It appears to be rather large, dark colored, with short tail feathers.

recordings.loc: Tucson, Pima, Arizona
recordings.rmk:
I have heard this bird on several separate occasions within the past few weeks, once at dusk but typically in the very early morning hours (0300–0500). The sounds toward the start of this recording are typical of what I've heard, though in some cases the hooting sound has been more prominent. Each time the bird has seemed to be high relative to the ground (on telephone poles or in trees). I have yet to see it, and it is rather shy (it stops calling as soon as I make any attempt to get closer).

My thinking is that it's a Long-Eared Owl, Asio otus, or possibly a Short-Eared Owl, Asio flammeus, but local experts I shared it with suggest perhaps a juvenile Great-Horned Owl or even a Spotted or Barred Owl.

The recording was made from inside a house through a security door, hence the poor sound quality. It has not been modified in any way. Habitat is a suburban residential neighborhood characterized by a variety of native and exotic trees, including many Prosopis as well as a variety of large Pinus and Eucalyptus.

recordings.file-name: XC612293-Great Horned Owl bill clicks on Old St Vrain Rd CO on 5.5.20 at 7.35 for .08.mp3
recordings.rmk: Juvenile had just fledged this AM. We inadvertently walked too close to the bird because we didn't see it. I heard the clicks first and saw it about 1 foot off ground on branch of a small bush. Recorded two sets of bill clicks and moved away because we didn't want to disturbe the bird any longer. Terrible recording in the wind. You can heard the double bill clicks at :03 and :06.
